    <centralBlocks>
      <Value><![CDATA[[
  {
    "key": "43008412-24bb-40dc-8e14-98eea53922d0",
    "name": "Health Interventions in Fragile and Conflict-Affected Settings (PgCert): More information and what you will achieve",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Health Interventions in Fragile and Conflict-Affected Settings (PgCert): More information and what you will achieve",
    "content": "<p>On this course, you will examine the concepts of vulnerability and resilience of individuals, households and their interaction with health systems in conflict and post-conflict settings, as well as strategies for strengthening the health system in fragile states. Re-establishing human resource systems provision and psychosocial interventions in a range of crisis settings is also part of this coherent course. </p>\n<p>When you have completed this course, you will be able to critically analyse and respond effectively and appropriately to complex policy and practice issues in diverse range of settings affected by conflict or emerging from conflict, as well as to integrate diverse perspectives on the impact of conflict to formulate effective and appropriate programmatic response to identified needs. </p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "39e051ec-3617-4a02-be13-36c4add74e99",
    "name": "How will I be taught?",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "How will I be taught?",
    "content": "<p><strong>Structure and exit awards</strong></p>\n<p>You can opt to study for the PgCert (60 credits) or you can also register as an associate student to complete a single module for CPD. On completion of a single module, you may wish to complete further modules and progress your studies to a named award. For the PgCert, in addition to the compulsory modules, a variety of modules can be studied, including our <a href=\"/study-here/continuing-professional-development-cpd-courses/cpd-courses-folder/forced-displacement-and-integration/\"><strong>Forced Displacement and Integration Module. </strong></a>Contact <a href=\"/schools-and-divisions/ighd/\"><strong>IGHD</strong></a> for more information.</p>\n<p><strong>Teaching, learning and assessment</strong></p>\n<p>Teaching is delivered face-to-face and online (asynchronous) and comprised of a combination of lectures, seminars, tutorials, case studies, discussion board, simulation exercises and projects. Assessment is continuous and incorporates assignments, action plans, projects and presentations.</p>\n<p><strong>Teaching hours and attendance</strong></p>\n<p>Your exact attendance requirements at QMU will depend on the module you are studying. In addition, for each module students spend approximately 10-12 hours of each week on preparatory class work independently and with colleagues, including readings and exercises available on dedicated web-based learning platforms.</p>\n<p><strong>Class sizes</strong></p>\n<p>We expect approximately 15-20 students to enroll for this course each year.</p>\n<p><strong>Teaching staff</strong></p>\n<p>You can read more about the teaching staff on this course at the bottom of this page. Please note that teaching staff is subject to change.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "4f5abcc4-45d5-4c8a-8c54-88c051f6c968",
    "name": "Modules",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Modules",
    "content": "<ul>\n<li>Health Systems in Fragile Setting (online) (15 credits) </li>\n<li>Psychosocial Interventions for Displaced Populations (15 credits) </li>\n<li>Independent Study (focusing on a topic relevant to health in fragile and conflict-affected settings). </li>\n<li>plus one more 15-credit module from the list of modules available at IGHD, which are subject to student demand. </li>\n</ul>\n<p>NB The modules listed are correct at time of publication (October 2023) but are subject to change. In the event that modules change, QMU will seek to use reasonable endeavours to ensure that there is no detrimental impact on students.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "0b7053d3-e29f-4eb3-9484-2d9e3afddad5",
    "name": "Career opportunities",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Career opportunities",
    "content": "<p>Our courses have been helping people to successfully advance their careers in global health for many years. Former IGHD students work in a variety of settings where a social development understanding informs approaches to health.</p>\n<p>Examples of positions filled by IGHD graduates include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Health Advisor for Save the Children UK</li>\n<li>Senior Co-ordinator for International Operations with Partners in Health</li>\n<li>Policy Development Officer in the Scottish NGO sector</li>\n<li>Public Health Policy Workers for First Nation’s communities in Canada</li>\n<li>Humanitarian worker with Islamic Relief</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Others have taken internships with organisations such as the WHO on graduation, while others have progressed to doctoral studies.</p>\n<p>As a graduate of the PgCert Health Interventions in Fragile and Conflict-Affected Settings, you will have the skills and understanding that are attractive to organisations working in some of the most vulnerable and at-risk communities in the world.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "f08456dc-c6ae-4d98-9a5d-0b54817bae32",
    "name": "Health Interventions in Fragile and Conflict-Affected Settings (PgCert): Entry requirements and application information",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Health Interventions in Fragile and Conflict-Affected Settings (PgCert): Entry requirements and application information",
    "content": "<p><strong>Entry requirements</strong></p>\n<p>A UK honours degree or equivalent from a relevant subject area (arts, humanities, health or social sciences). Students without an honours degree may be considered if they have other relevant qualifications and/or appropriate work experience. </p>\n<p>International: Where your honours degree has not been studied in English, you will be required to take an IELTS test receiving an overall score of 6.0 and no individual component score below 5.5. </p>\n<p><span class=\"NormalTextRun SCXW165835972 BCX0\">NB This course is only open to applicants who do not require a student visa to study in the UK. </span></p>\n<p><strong>Applying for this course</strong></p>\n<p>For more information on applying, or to apply for this course, please follow the links in the 'Start your application' box at the top right of this page.</p>\n<p><strong>Application deadline</strong></p>\n<p>End of December 2024</p>\n<p><strong>Terms and Conditions</strong></p>\n<p>The delivery of this course is subject to the terms and conditions set out in our <a href=\"/current-students/current-students-general-information/matriculation-and-enrolment/applicant-and-student-terms-and-conditions/\" title=\"Applicant and Student Terms and Conditions\">2024/25 Entry - Terms and Conditions (Postgraduate).</a></p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "a96ec91f-d041-4162-8e10-69b395cc47a0",
    "name": "More information and QMU contacts",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "More information and QMU contacts",
    "content": "<p><a href=\"mailto:admissions@qmu.ac.uk\" title=\"Contact Admissions\">Contact Admissions</a> or <a href=\"mailto:ighd@qmu.ac.uk\">contact IGHD</a> for more information.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "25481dea-1910-401e-95d8-6e314c044f8c",
    "name": "Opportunities to meet us",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Opportunities to meet us",
    "content": "<p><a href=\"/{localLink:umb://document/fde923ae229e4d59916e57b4c164f7c1}\" title=\"Open Days and Meeting Us\">Please click for information on our forthcoming open events.</a></p>"
  }
]]]></Value>
